---
import Narrative from '../layouts/Narrative.astro';
---
<Narrative title="Why This Exists — CommonGround">

  <!-- ─── Scene 1 · Hero ─────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="scene vision-hero grid">
    <div class="col-wide vision-hero-inner">
      <p class="label vision-hero-label" data-hero-wordmark>CommonGround · Vision</p>
      <h1 class="vision-headline" data-hero-tagline>
        Something was lost.<br>We are building it back.
      </h1>
      <p class="vision-lede measure" data-hero-rung>
        This is not a technology story. It is a story about what human beings need
        from one another, what we have been deprived of, and what it might look
        like to choose differently.
      </p>
    </div>
    <a class="vision-scroll label" href="#scene-diagnosis" data-hero-scroll aria-label="Continue reading">
      <span class="vision-scroll-arrow" aria-hidden="true">↓</span>
      <span>Continue reading</span>
    </a>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Scene 2 · The Diagnosis ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section id="scene-diagnosis" class="scene grid">

    <div class="col-margin diagnosis-aside" data-reveal>
      <p class="label">I · Diagnosis</p>
    </div>

    <div class="col-center vision-prose">

      <div class="vision-problem" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-problem-heading">We have become strangers to each other</h2>
        <p>
          For most of human history, the immediate world was the social world.
          You knew your neighbors not as an aspiration but as a fact of daily
          life. You relied on them — for labor at harvest, for watch kept over
          children, for the quiet knowledge that someone would notice if you
          went three days without opening your door. That web of mutual
          attention was not sentimental. It was structural. It did things.
        </p>
        <p>
          What replaced it was not malice but design. Cities were built for
          movement and commerce. Suburbs were engineered for privacy. Schedules
          were organized around the workplace. The informal social infrastructure
          — the front porch, the corner store, the parish hall, the village
          green — was not destroyed so much as designed out, one quiet zoning
          ordinance and one highway interchange at a time.
        </p>
        <p>
          The result is a peculiar modern loneliness that is invisible because
          it is universal. We call it busyness. We call it preference. We call
          it introversion. We rarely call it what it is: a collective deprivation
          that no individual can solve alone, because it was not created by
          individuals acting alone.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="ornament"><span class="dot"></span></div>

      <div class="vision-problem" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-problem-heading">We have forgotten how to live in a place</h2>
        <p>
          For ten thousand years, most people could tell you which plants came
          up first in spring, which fields held water in a dry year, which
          hillside the deer preferred in November. They could name the birds
          and predict the weather and read the land with the accumulated
          knowledge of generations. That knowledge was not merely practical.
          It was a form of belonging — to a specific piece of earth, to the
          cycle of seasons, to something larger and older than any single life.
        </p>
        <p>
          Urban modernity dissolved that bond with astonishing speed. Most
          people alive today do not know where their food comes from, which
          watershed they drink from, or what ecological community their
          neighborhood once supported. This is not ignorance — it is severance.
          We have been systematically cut off from the rhythms and relationships
          that oriented human life for millennia, and then told to fill the gap
          with consumption.
        </p>
        <p>
          The cost is not only ecological, though it is that too. It is a cost
          to the self — a faint, persistent homesickness for a home we were
          never taught to make. The hunger for farmers markets, community
          gardens, and wild foraging is not a trend. It is a symptom. People
          are trying to find their way back to something they cannot quite name.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="ornament"><span class="dot"></span></div>

      <div class="vision-problem" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-problem-heading">The ceremonies have gone quiet</h2>
        <p>
          Community is not only a matter of proximity and mutual aid. It is
          also a matter of meaning — of the shared rituals, ceremonies, and
          public practices through which people remind themselves that they
          belong to something together. The harvest festival. The neighborhood
          feast. The public mourning. The seasonal market that was also a
          social event. The town meeting that was also a performance of
          collective identity.
        </p>
        <p>
          These practices did something that no algorithm can replicate: they
          created a shared symbolic life. They gave communities a way to mark
          time, honor the dead, celebrate the living, and rehearse the values
          they wanted to hold. When they disappear, something goes with them
          that is hard to name but immediately felt — a kind of thinness, a
          sense that we are passing through a place rather than inhabiting it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The hunger for this is visible everywhere. People create rituals at
          vigils and pop-up shrines. Farmers markets become pseudo-civic
          gatherings. Community dinners sell out in hours. The impulse is not
          nostalgic — it is fundamental. Human beings need to mark time
          together, need ceremonies that make meaning legible to the body.
          We have not outgrown that need. We have simply lost the structures
          that used to meet it.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Scene 3 · The Pivot ─────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="scene scene-pivot grid">
    <div class="col-center stanza pivot-stanza" data-reveal>
      <p>This is not nostalgia</p>
      <p>What was lost was not perfect.</p>
      <p>Much of it was unjust, parochial, exclusionary.</p>
      <p>We are not trying to recover the past.</p>
      <p><em>We are trying to recover the function.</em></p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Scene 4 · What Is the Commons ──────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="scene grid">

    <div class="col-margin commons-aside" data-reveal>
      <p class="label">II · The Commons</p>
    </div>

    <div class="col-center vision-prose">

      <div class="vision-block" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-block-heading">Infrastructure, not ideology</h2>
        <p>
          The word "commons" carries ideological freight it doesn't need. Strip
          it back and it means something simple: resources, spaces, and
          practices that are held and managed collectively, for the benefit of
          a community over time. A library is commons infrastructure. So is a
          neighborhood tool share, a community orchard, a water management
          cooperative, a seed library, a co-working space governed by its
          members.
        </p>
        <p>
          What makes something commons infrastructure is not ownership in the
          legal sense. It is the relationship people have to it — one of shared
          responsibility, shared benefit, and shared governance. The commons is
          built on the recognition that some things work better when we hold
          them together than when we divide them up and hold them separately.
          Not because of sentiment, but because the math works out that way.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="vision-block" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-block-heading">Ritual as civic technology</h2>
        <p>
          Civic rituals — the gatherings, ceremonies, and seasonal practices
          that mark time in a community — are not decoration. They are
          technology. They are the means by which communities reproduce
          themselves, transmit values across generations, process collective
          grief and joy, and remind their members that they are in relationship
          with one another and with the land.
        </p>
        <p>
          Rebuilding civic ritual does not mean reviving old forms for their
          own sake. It means creating new forms — or adapting old ones — that
          serve the same function in contemporary contexts. A community harvest
          dinner. A neighborhood skill share. An annual gathering to tend the
          commons. These are not quaint. They are load-bearing.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="vision-block" data-reveal>
        <h2 class="vision-block-heading">Stewardship as identity</h2>
        <p>
          The deepest thing the consumer society cost us was not convenience
          in reverse — it was a way of understanding ourselves. For most of
          human history, most people thought of themselves as stewards: of
          land, of craft, of memory, of future generations. You cared for
          something beyond yourself, and that care gave you a place in the
          story.
        </p>
        <p>
          The commons is, at its root, an invitation back into that story.
          Not through obligation or guilt, but through the practical
          experience of tending something together — watching it improve under
          shared care, watching it fail under neglect, learning through that
          feedback loop what it means to be responsible for something larger
          than your own life. That experience changes people. It is, perhaps,
          the most reliable civic education we know of.
        </p>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ─── Scene 5 · The Invitation ────────────────────────────────── -->
  <section class="scene scene-invitation grid">

    <div class="col-center vision-invitation" data-reveal>
      <p class="label" style="margin-bottom: 20px;">III · Possibility</p>
      <h2 class="vision-invitation-heading">
        People are already doing this.
      </h2>
      <div class="vision-invitation-body measure">
        <p>
          In every city and town we have looked at, people are quietly
          rebuilding. Community land trusts. Tool libraries. Seed swaps.
          Neighborhood composts. Repair cafés. Mutual aid networks that
          formed during crisis and never dissolved. Cooperatives of every
          description. A thousand small acts of collective care that never
          make the news because they are not in conflict with anything —
          they are simply people choosing, over and over, to hold something
          together.
        </p>
        <p>
          What is mostly missing is not the will. It is the infrastructure:
          the shared tools, the governance templates, the communication
          systems, the institutional memory, the connections between efforts
          that would make each one stronger by virtue of what the others
          are learning. What is missing is the operating layer that would
          let these efforts find each other, build on each other, and
          compound over time into something durable.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is what we are building. Not a platform in the extractive
          sense — not a system that aggregates community activity in order
          to sell it back. A commons infrastructure for commons building.
          Tools that are owned by the communities that use them. Governance
          that is designed from the start to resist capture. Memory that
          belongs to the people who made it.
        </p>
        <p>
          The question was never whether people want to live this way. They
          always have. The question is whether we build the conditions that
          make it possible — whether we do it deliberately, carefully, and
          well enough that it lasts.
        </p>
        <p class="vision-invitation-close">
          We think that is worth trying.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="vision-invitation-ctas">
        <a href="/manifesto" class="vision-cta">Read the manifesto →</a>
        <a href="/patterns" class="vision-cta">See the patterns →</a>
        <a href="/start-here" class="vision-cta">Start here →</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <p class="label vision-footer col-wide" data-reveal>CommonGround · Vol. I · Spring 2026</p>

  </section>

</Narrative>

<style>
  /* ── Hero ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .vision-hero {
    min-height: 100dvh;
    align-items: center;
    position: relative;
  }
  .vision-hero-inner {
    grid-column: 2 / 9;
    padding-top: 88px;
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }
  .vision-hero-label {
    margin-bottom: 32px;
  }
  .vision-headline {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(44px, 6vw, 88px);
    font-weight: 400;
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 0 0 36px;
  }
  .vision-lede {
    font-size: clamp(18px, 1.5vw, 22px);
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--muted);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .vision-scroll {
    position: absolute;
    bottom: 48px;
    left: 50%;
    transform: translateX(-50%);
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 10px;
    color: var(--muted);
    text-decoration: none;
    padding: 8px 14px;
  }
  .vision-scroll:hover { color: var(--ink); }
  .vision-scroll-arrow {
    display: inline-block;
    animation: vision-bob 2.4s ease-in-out infinite;
    animation-delay: 2s;
  }
  @keyframes vision-bob {
    0%, 100% { transform: translateY(0); }
    50%       { transform: translateY(4px); }
  }

  /* ── Shared prose column ──────────────────────────────────────── */
  .vision-prose {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 0;
  }
  .diagnosis-aside,
  .commons-aside {
    padding-top: 8px;
  }

  /* ── Problem / block sections ─────────────────────────────────── */
  .vision-problem,
  .vision-block {
    margin-bottom: 72px;
  }
  .vision-problem:last-child,
  .vision-block:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .vision-problem-heading,
  .vision-block-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(22px, 2vw, 30px);
    font-weight: 500;
    line-height: 1.2;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
    margin: 0 0 24px;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .vision-prose p {
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
    line-height: var(--fs-body-lh);
    color: var(--ink);
    max-width: 68ch;
    margin: 0 0 20px;
  }
  .vision-prose p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  /* ── Pivot scene ──────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .scene-pivot {
    border-top: 0.5px solid var(--rule);
    border-bottom: 0.5px solid var(--rule);
  }
  .pivot-stanza p {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
  }
  .pivot-stanza p em {
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  /* ── Invitation scene ─────────────────────────────────────────── */
  .scene-invitation {
    border-top: 0.5px solid var(--rule);
    row-gap: 48px;
    align-items: start;
    padding-bottom: 80px;
  }
  .vision-invitation {
    padding-top: 24px;
  }
  .vision-invitation-heading {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: clamp(36px, 4.5vw, 64px);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.1;
    margin: 0 0 40px;
    color: var(--ink);
  }
  .vision-invitation-body p {
    font-size: var(--fs-body);
    line-height: var(--fs-body-lh);
    color: var(--ink);
    margin: 0 0 20px;
  }
  .vision-invitation-body p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }
  .vision-invitation-close {
    font-style: italic;
    font-size: clamp(20px, 2vw, 26px);
    color: var(--ink);
    margin-top: 36px;
  }
  .vision-invitation-ctas {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 14px;
    margin-top: 56px;
  }
  .vision-cta {
    font-size: 20px;
    color: var(--ink);
    text-decoration-color: var(--rule);
    text-underline-offset: 6px;
    width: fit-content;
    transition: color 0.15s ease, text-decoration-color 0.15s ease;
  }
  .vision-cta:hover {
    color: var(--accent);
    text-decoration-color: var(--accent);
  }
  .vision-footer {
    grid-column: 2 / 12;
    text-align: center;
    color: var(--muted);
    padding-top: 0;
    margin-top: auto;
  }

  /* ── Responsive ───────────────────────────────────────────────── */
  @media (max-width: 900px) {
    .vision-hero-inner {
      grid-column: 1 / -1;
      padding-left: 0;
    }
    .col-margin.diagnosis-aside,
    .col-margin.commons-aside {
      grid-column: 1 / -1;
      margin-bottom: 0;
    }
    .col-center.vision-prose,
    .col-center.pivot-stanza,
    .col-center.vision-invitation {
      grid-column: 1 / -1;
    }
    .vision-footer {
      grid-column: 1 / -1;
    }
  }

  @media (max-width: 600px) {
    .vision-headline {
      font-size: clamp(36px, 10vw, 56px);
    }
    .vision-invitation-heading {
      font-size: clamp(30px, 8vw, 48px);
    }
  }
</style>
